,"Dorset, England":"Dorset, England, United Kingdom","Birling, Sussex, England":"Sussex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Beard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","nickname for a bearded man (from Middle English <i>berd</i>, Old English <i>beard</i>). To be clean-shaven was the norm in non-Jewish communities in northwestern Europe from the 12th to the 16th century, the crucial period for surname formation. There is a placename and other evidence to show that this word was used as a byname in the Old English period, when beards were the norm; in this period the byname would have referred to a large or noticeable beard. In North America, this surname has absorbed cognates and equivalents in other languages, in particular German   Barth   1.","habitational name from a place called Beard in Derbyshire (now represented by Beard Hall and Beardwood Farms in New Mills parish), which derives its name by dissimilation from Old English <i>brerd</i> ‘rim, bank’."],"variants":[{"name":"Bardwell","meanings":["English (Suffolk): habitational name from Bardwell in Suffolk, so named with an unattested Old English byname <i>Bearda</i>, a derivative of <i>beard</i> (see   Beard  ) + Old English <i>well(a)</i> ‘spring, stream’. Alternatively, the first element may be from a dissimilated form of Old English <i>bre(o)rd</i> ‘brim, bank’."]},{"name":"Barth","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Hans, Kurt, Franz, Erwin, Florian, Gerhard, Gunther, Klaus, Manfred, Armin, Arno.","German and Swiss German: nickname for a bearded man, from Middle High German <i>bart</i> ‘beard’. This name, which can not be always distinguished from 2 and 4 below, is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine), Poland, Czechia, Slovakia, and Slovenia, in the last four countries sometimes as a German translation of Slavic surnames meaning ‘beard’ or ‘bearded man’ (see   Bart   1). See also   Beard   1.","German: habitational name from a place so named in Pomerania."]},{"name":"Bard","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Michel, Aime, Alphonse, Alphy, Armand, Cecile, Celestine, Emile, Fernand, Germaine, Gilles, Jacques.","English (of Norman origin) and French: from the Old French personal name <i>Bard(e)</i>, ancient Germanic <i>Bardo</i>, from <i>barta</i> ‘battle axe’. This was borne as a surname by a prominent Norman family with lands in west Normandy and in various English and Scottish counties, including Essex, Hertfordshire, North Yorkshire, Northumberland, and Lanarkshire. In Scotland the original family were Norman landowners in Strathaven parish in Lanarkshire. They were descended from the Baards, lords of Loftus in the North Yorkshire, descendants of the mid 12th-century Richard <i>Baart</i>.","Irish: altered form of either   Beard   or   Baird  ."]},{"name":"Bearb","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Aurelien, Camille, Micheline, Pierre.","Altered form of English   Beard  , under the influence, in LA, of French <i>barbe</i> ‘beard’."]}]},{"name":"Ellen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Helen  , although now no longer associated with that name. Initial <i>H-</i> tended to be added and dropped rather capriciously, leading to many doublets (  compare for example  Esther   and   Hester  ). It is also sometimes used as a short form of   Eleanor  , to which, however, it is unrelated."],"variants":[{"name":"Eleanor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Ellen Beard was born as the daughter of Richard George Beard and Elizabeth MNU Hogg. She had at least 6 sons and 1 daughter with Robert Jennens."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1530–Male":"1530–Surnud","1532–1602":"1532–1602","1533–1602":"1533–1602","1550–1598":"1550–1598","1550–1651":"1550–1651","1559–1602":"1559–1602","1492–1526":"1492–1526","1602":"1602","1533":"1533","1532":"1532","1598":"1598","1530":"1530","1651":"1651","1550":"1550","1492":"1492","1518":"1518","1559":"1559","1526":"1526","Birringham, Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Craven, Yorkshire, England":"Craven, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ebor, Craven, Yorkshire, England":"Craven, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Dorset, England":"Dorset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Birling, Sussex, England":"Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1530–Male":"1530–Kuollut","1532–1602":"1532–1602","1533–1602":"1533–1602","1550–1598":"1550–1598","1550–1651":"1550–1651","1559–1602":"1559–1602","1492–1526":"1492–1526","1602":"1602","1533":"1533","1532":"1532","1598":"1598","1530":"1530","1651":"1651","1550":"1550","1492":"1492","1518":"1518","1559":"1559","1526":"1526","Birringham, Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Craven, Yorkshire, England":"Craven, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Ebor, Craven, Yorkshire, England":"Craven, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Dorset, England":"Dorset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Birling, Sussex, England":"Sussex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"–":"Décédée","–Female":"Décédée","–Male":"Décédé","1530–Male":"1530–Décédé","1532–1602":"15